    <h2 class="govuk-heading-m" id="viewing-cases">
      6. Viewing and restricting cases
    </h2>

    <p>
      Most cases can be viewed by all users of the Product Safety Database - this enables information sharing and collaboration.
    </p>

    <p>
      Teams are encouraged to browse products and cases that may relate to ongoing investigations and to collaborate with other authorities as appropriate before submitting cases.
    </p>

    <h3 class="govuk-heading-s">
      Protecting sensitive case details
    </h3>

    <p>
      Where appropriate, the PSD protects information that should not be viewable by all users. Items likely to contain sensitive information can only be viewed by teams added to a case. Teams not involved in a case will be able to see that those items exist but will not be able to view them.
    </p>

    <p>
      Items that can only be seen by teams added to a case:
    </p>

    <ul class="govuk-list govuk-list--bullet">
      <li>correspondence and their attachments</li>
      <li>enquiry source contact details</li>
      <li>‘generic attachments’ - attachments that are not connected to another document like a test result or corrective action</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      If further case details need to be protected, the case should be restricted so that it cannot be viewed by teams not added to a case.
    </p>


    <h3 class="govuk-heading-s">
      Restricting access to cases
    </h3>

    <p>
      The information shared in the PSD can only be seen by registered users from market surveillance authorities and OPSS. Case owners can ‘restrict’ cases which means that only teams that are added to a case can view it.
    </p>

    <p>
      The aim of the PSD is to share information within the product safety community to save time, effort, and money. Therefore, cases should only be restricted in exceptional circumstances, for example, if visibility may impinge upon a legal proceeding.
    </p>

    <p>
      When you restrict a case, you’ll be asked to give a reason for the change. This reason helps others know why the restriction has happened. It will also be visible to teams that are not involved in the case.
    </p>

    <p>
      Teams added to the case will be able to see all case details. If the case owner removes a team from a case, that team will no longer be able to view it.
    </p>

    <p>
      Products and businesses attached to restricted cases will remain visible to all users.
    </p>

    <p>
      You can restrict a case from the 'Sharing and collaboration' section of the case overview.
    </p>

    <h3 class="govuk-heading-s">
      Administrator access
    </h3>

    <p>
      Some staff at OPSS have administrator access to the PSD.
    </p>

    <p>
      This allows them to:
    </p>

    <ul class="govuk-list govuk-list--bullet">
      <li>
        view and edit all case details, including cases they are not involved in
      </li>
      <li>
        view all restricted cases
      </li>
      <li>
        export details of cases added to the PSD
      </li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      This level of access is provided to a small number of people to ensure that OPSS can view all product safety information on the PSD. This ensures that, as an evidence-based regulator, strategic intelligence assessments and market surveillance activity is as robust and targeted as possible.
    </p>

    <h2 class="govuk-heading-m" id="collaborating-on-cases">
      7. Collaborating with other market surveillance authorities and teams
    </h2>

    <h3 class="govuk-heading-s">Case owners</h3>

    <p>
      All cases have a ‘case owner’ - the person or team responsible for the case. The case owner may collaborate on a case with other teams or assign the case to another team as needed.
    </p>

    <p>
      Where the case owner is a person, their team also owns the case - anyone in their team has full rights over the case.
    </p>

    <p>
      Only case owners can change:
    </p>

    <ul class="govuk-list govuk-list--bullet">
      <li>the case owner to someone else</li>
      <li>the case status (open or closed)</li>
      <li>the case restriction status</li>
      <li>the teams added to the case</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      When a case is first created, the person who created it becomes the case owner.
    </p>

    <h3 class="govuk-heading-s">
      Teams added to a case
    </h3>

     <p>
      Teams can be added to a case with 'view' or 'edit' permissions. Teams added with edit permissions will be able to make changes to the case and will be able to view protected details, like correspondence. Teams added with view only permissions will be able to view protected details but will not be able to make changes to the case.
    </p>

    <p>
      You should add a team to a case if you want them to be able to view the full case or add further details. If a team no longer needs access to the case, you can remove them.
    </p>


    <h3 class="govuk-heading-s">
      Changing the case owner
    </h3>

    <p>
      Only the current case owner can assign a new owner.
    </p>

    <p>
      To change the case owner to another authority or team, navigate to the ‘Sharing and collaboration’ section of the case overview. The new case owner will be notified that they’ve been made the case owner via email. You can also include a message that will be sent to them - so you can let them know why you’re assigning them the case.
    </p>

    <p>
      When the case owner changes, the previous case owner’s team remains added to the case.
    </p>

    <h2 class="govuk-heading-m" id="managing-your-team-and-account">
      8. Managing your team and account
    </h2>

    <h3 class="govuk-heading-s">
      Giving your team access to the PSD
    </h3>

    <p>
      Officers who lead on product safety from each market surveillance authority have been given a PSD account and made a ‘team administrator’. Once they’ve set up their own account, they can invite other colleagues – from their organisation only – to create an account too. They can do this by going to the ‘Your team’ part of the service, adding their colleague’s email address and choosing ‘Invite’.
    </p>

    <h3 class="govuk-heading-s">
      Administrators can add another administrator
    </h3>

    <p>
      If there’s someone in the team whose responsibilities make them better placed to be an administrator – for example, they will regularly lead work connected with the PSD – invite them to create an account. You can then email <%= mail_to t(:enquiries_email), nil, class: "govuk-link" %> and ask for them to be made a team admin.
    </p>

    <h3 class="govuk-heading-s">
      Updating your account details
    </h3>

    <p>
      You can update your name yourself by going to the ‘Your account’ part of the service.
    </p>

    <p>
      To update your password, sign out of the service and use the ‘Forgot your password’ link when signing in.
    </p>

    <p>
      You can update your contact details, your team or organisation’s details, or delete your account by emailing <%= mail_to t(:enquiries_email), nil, class: "govuk-link" %> to:
    </p>



